page.title: 14WILDLIFE IN THE GREAT PARK
page.content: Together with the New Forest, Windsor Great Park has the widest range of wild life of any area in England. There are 2,000 different species of beetle alone and many other insects are found there. The Nature Conservancy Board have designated much of this region as an area of special scientfic interest. None of the trees can be moved, even when they have fallen down, because this could destroy a whole species. There are many rabbits and foxes, but few badgers now. A corner of the deer park is in this area. Blackbirds, song and mistle thrushes are here all the year; redwings and fieldfares visit in winter. Canada geese, mandarin duck and the great crested grebe live on ponds in the Park. Occasionally a tawny owl can be seen.
